{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17886"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0,0.92,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96676"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5102"},{"type":"tags","id":"10067"},{"type":"tags","id":"10068"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucagon is a hormone produced by the alpha cells in the islets of Langerhans.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is its action on the liver during fasting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreases gluconeogenesis","Decreases ketone production","Increases fatty acid synthesis","Increases glycogen breakdown","Increases glycogen synthesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glycogen breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E is a primary action of glucagon on the liver during fasting. Glucagon stimulates glycogenolysis, which is the breakdown of glycogen into glucose, to maintain blood glucose levels when dietary intake is low.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased fatty acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not an action of glucagon. Instead, glucagon promotes the breakdown of fatty acids for energy production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased gluconeogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Glucagon actually increases gluconeogenesis, which is the production of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources, to help maintain blood glucose levels during fasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glycogen synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Glucagon decreases glycogen synthesis as it promotes the breakdown of glycogen to release glucose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased ketone production\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. During prolonged fasting, glucagon promotes ketogenesis, which is the production of ketone bodies from fatty acids, as an alternative energy source.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucagon increases glycogenolysis in the liver during fasting.","Glucagon promotes gluconeogenesis to maintain blood glucose levels.","Glucagon decreases glycogen synthesis in the liver."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 79, pg. 982.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. 4th ed. Chichester: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647.","Wang Y, Wu R. The Effect of Fasting on Human Metabolism and Psychological Health. Dis Markers. 2022 Jan 5;2022:5653739.","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, Glucose Metabolism. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan. 2023 Jul 17.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96676"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96676"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T15:01:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T15:01:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10600"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com